node.text:
If I tell my story, perhaps you’ll feel like you can tell yours too. And that’s all I could ever hope for in this wild and sometimes lonely world…
———————————
📷: @mary.scinto

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Brianna Madia on July 30, 2021. May be an image of nature.

node.text:
My decision to not have children feels different as a single woman.
And I feel like I need to acknowledge how significant that difference is and how much I admire and honor the single, child-free women who have hurrahed right along with my posts all these years…the posts about how “alone” I felt in that choice, all whilst having a supportive partner beside me.
Well, shit. I’m definitely alone in that choice now.
I still feel beyond secure in it, but I am so much more aware of its consequences.

“Dealbreaker.”
That’s the word that bounces off the walls of my mind. I remember friends scrolling through dating profiles, reading certain details…
Political affiliation: Dealbreaker!
Religious beliefs: Dealbreaker!
Smoker: Dealbreaker!
A woman who does not want children is absolutely a dealbreaker for many potential partners. And that’s understandable.
I would *never* want to deprive someone of such a significant part of the future they’ve imagined for themselves.

And so, the concept of a partner seems a bit further off sometimes, and that has made me question things I’ve never had to before. But my conclusion day after day is that I already know the answer to those questions.

Because night after night, even though I lay down by myself, I sleep well knowing that I’m truly being myself.

node.text:
Yesterday my mom and I were talking on the phone and she was listing off all these big, stressful things and huge potential life changes coming up and all the planning and figuring out she’s gotta do. And then she sighed and said, “…anyway, I’m not gonna let it ruin my afternoon.” 😂 and THAT is the energy 🙏

Also, the stoke is very very high because my mama is coming down to Mexico on Sunday to stay with me for a week 🌴🍹👯‍♀️
———————————
📷: @mary.scinto

node.text:
In college, I wrote a nonfiction essay that my professor persuaded me to submit to a local writing contest.
It was about a pair of boots.
I mapped my adolescence on them.
Scratches from jumping fences at Dave Matthews concerts, cigarette burns from an old boyfriend...
I won the contest.
Professors from all over Rhode Island described me with such words as “talented” and “promising” and my imposter syndrome screamed, “this is the smallest state in the country, the pool wasn’t that big, don’t you forget that, Brianna…”

For years afterward, I was convinced that that was the only beautiful thing that was ever going to come out of my body. After all, I sat down one afternoon on the back deck of an apartment I shared with 5 other girls and vomited it up - handwritten - in under 45 minutes. Like it was stuck somewhere in there for years. It seemed like an accident, not a talent.
So I didn’t write anything else after that.
I didn’t write anything else for seven years.
In fact, I only started writing again because of this app. This god-forsaken app. Only I didn’t think of it like that back then. I didn’t have the twinge of bitterness that causes me to grit my teeth when I say it now. Back then, Instagram was anonymity and, in that, there was safety. There was no blue check mark. I was not some verified version of myself. That thought was so far off it can hardly be considered a thought at all.
I started writing again just to write, and what happened here on my phone is that…you told me I was good. You didn’t owe me that. I was nobody to you. But you told me I was good. And after so many years of believing I had left every ounce of creativity between the splintered boards of that back deck…that was everything to me.

I wish I could tell you I’m one of those creatives who knew they’d “be something!” someone who “believed in themselves when no one else did!”
But I’m not.
I needed to be lifted up until I could stand on my own…and that’s okay. I’m 31-years-old now, and I’m still finding my balance; knees still knocking like a newborn animal.
But I’m standing nonetheless, and though I may still admit it through gritted teeth…I owe so much of that to this god forsaken app.

node.text: He was worth it all. I promise you. Say whatever you need to say. Throw at me whatever you feel needs throwing. He was worth it all. He was 👏WORTH👏IT👏ALL👏

node.text:
I am a sturdy soul,
and there ain’t no shame,
in lying down in the bed you made.
Can you fight the urge to run for another day...
You might make it further, if you learn to stay.
- Brandi Carlile
